<details><summary>Increase in tech debt: (relative, absolute) = (1.00, 0.00)</summary>

|Current number|Change|Type|
|-:|:-:|:-|
|1515|1|erw|

Current commit [86354aa6dd](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/commit/86354aa6ddcece90af24c7e115d30ef969fd0427)
Reference commit [c93dd21f32](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/commit/c93dd21f321c9fe77ab73aecf674178a6af5ce5e)

You can run this locally as
```
./scripts/technical-debt-metrics.sh pr_summary
```
* The `relative` value is the weighted *sum* of the differences with weight given by the *inverse* of the current value of the statistic.
* The `absolute` value is the `relative` value divided by the total sum of the inverses of the current values (i.e. the weighted *average* of the differences).
</details>

I don't really get the motivation here. Why would we write a much more complex proof of the denumerability of rational numbers if the one we have already works?

If the idea is that this new equivalence is better computationally, then perhaps it can instead be written as a new `def continuedFractionEquiv : â„• â‰ƒ â„š` rather than trying to overwrite the existing instance? If that's not the case, then the new continued fraction API is welcome, but I don't think the denumerability part is necessary at all.

> I don't really get the motivation here. Why would we write a much more complex proof of the denumerability of rational numbers if the one we have already works?
> 
> If the idea is that this new equivalence is better computationally, then perhaps it can instead be written as a new `def continuedFractionEquiv : â„• â‰ƒ â„š` rather than trying to overwrite the existing instance? If that's not the case, then the new continued fraction API is welcome, but I don't think the denumerability part is necessary at all.

My take on this is that anything we want a computable implementation of, we want a fast computable implementation of. I'm not quite sure why we need computable denumerability of Q at all to be honest, but if we have it it might as well be fast. The old implementation was mega slow, it relied on counting the number of non-coprime pairs that had been skipped out, so to `decode` n you had to evaluate `decode m` for all `m` less than `n`.
Hm, that's fair enough. I imagine if someone doesn't care about computability but still need an instance of this (for whatever reason) they can use `Denumerable.ofEncodableOfInfinite` directly.

This PR/issue depends on:
* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#18584~~
* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#18581~~
* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#18589~~
